title: Analysis of SensorLog Data
text: vignette, go steps analyze SensorLog data. go steps reading data, checking potential duplicates timestamps, calculating distance metrics fixed point (commonly participant home), creating daily summaries. also integrate ActiGraph data show activity different distances.

title: Analysis of SensorLog Data
text: data used example data embedded waterways package. single participant approximately two hours worth GPS activity data. SensorLog data stored zip file contains single CSV file. data stored extdata folder package. can get path file user’s machines using system.file package name: can also done using wrapper waterways:
code: library(waterways) file = system.file(   "extdata", "SensorLogFiles_my_iOS_device_250311_14-55-58.zip",   package = "waterways") file #> [1] "/home/runner/work/_temp/Library/waterways/extdata/SensorLogFiles_my_iOS_device_250311_14-55-58.zip" ww_example_sensorlog_file() #> [1] "/home/runner/work/_temp/Library/waterways/extdata/SensorLogFiles_my_iOS_device_250311_14-55-58.zip"

title: Analysis of SensorLog Data
text: data read using ww_read_sensorlog function: option robust run rewrite_sensorlog_csv run data. rewrite_sensorlog_csv attempts fix shifts data, seen due bug iOS app. option default FALSE can take much longer time read data due reading writing data back temporary file. function also flag values latitude longitude 0 (absolute value <0.00001< 0.00001). flag created iOS app sometimes record 0 latitude longitude GPS signal lost. see data following columns, renamed original data. mapping new column names original column names can seen using ww_sensorlog_csv_colnames_mapping:
code: library(dplyr) df = ww_read_sensorlog(file, robust = FALSE) df = df %>% select(-file) # we don't need to see which file this came from head(df) #> # A tibble: 6 × 13 #>   time         index timestamp   lat   lon altitude speed speed_accuracy accel_X #>   <chr>        <dbl>     <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>    <dbl> <dbl>          <dbl>   <dbl> #> 1 2025-03-11T…     1    1.74e9  39.3 -76.6     46.3    -1             -1  0.411  #> 2 2025-03-11T…     2    1.74e9  39.3 -76.6     46.3    -1             -1  0.0908 #> 3 2025-03-11T…     3    1.74e9  39.3 -76.6     46.3    -1             -1  0.125  #> 4 2025-03-11T…     4    1.74e9  39.3 -76.6     46.3    -1             -1  0.0636 #> 5 2025-03-11T…     5    1.74e9  39.3 -76.6     46.3    -1             -1  0.0993 #> 6 2025-03-11T…     6    1.74e9  39.3 -76.6     46.3    -1             -1  0.0702 #> # ℹ 4 more variables: accel_Y <dbl>, accel_Z <dbl>, lat_zero <lgl>, #> #   lon_zero <lgl> colnames(df) #>  [1] "time"           "index"          "timestamp"      "lat"            #>  [5] "lon"            "altitude"       "speed"          "speed_accuracy" #>  [9] "accel_X"        "accel_Y"        "accel_Z"        "lat_zero"       #> [13] "lon_zero" ww_sensorlog_csv_colnames_mapping() #>                             time                            index  #>               "loggingTime(txt)"               "loggingSample(N)"  #>                        timestamp                              lat  #> "locationTimestamp_since1970(s)"        "locationLatitude(WGS84)"  #>                              lon                         altitude  #>       "locationLongitude(WGS84)"            "locationAltitude(m)"  #>                            speed                   speed_accuracy  #>             "locationSpeed(m/s)"     "locationSpeedAccuracy(m/s)"  #>                          accel_X                          accel_Y  #>  "accelerometerAccelerationX(G)"  "accelerometerAccelerationY(G)"  #>                          accel_Z  #>  "accelerometerAccelerationZ(G)"

title: Analysis of SensorLog Data
text: data processed using ww_process_sensorlog function. function (currently) : Check data duplicated data using ww_check_data. Calculate distance central point provided using ww_calculate_distance Process timing data using ww_process_time, including checking duplicate times. function also determine data correct timezone estimating timezone expected (expected_timezone field, set America/New_York) based GPS coordinates, using lutz::tz_lookup_coords function. check desired, set expected_timezone = NULL: error indicates, duplicate times file. can look specific duplicate times see even 3 digits milliseconds, multiple measurements: Thus, want ensure duplicated times, set check_data FALSE: data times projected GMT timezone agree output ActiGraph read.gt3x::read.gt3x. NOTE: shifts times original timezone. example, data “2025-03-25 14:14:00” timezone -04:00 data GMT timezone, printed time “2025-03-25 18:14:00 GMT”. can set timezone correct timezone using lubridate::with_tz lubridate::force_tz (different behavior). can also pass tz = "EST" argument ww_process_sensorlog, passed ww_process_time. additional column char_time added original character values fo time retained users can check timezone conversions, can lead issues merging data, determining windows (e.g. wake), time-based analyses.

title: Analysis of SensorLog Data
text: pass latitude longitude fixed point calculate distance processing function, . can also calculate distance separately using function ww_calculate_distance. First, need get latitude longitude fixed point. can use tidygeocoder package get latitude longitude fixed point. use address 615 N Wolfe St, Baltimore MD Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School Public Health data collected, using Census Geocoder free: can calculate distance fixed point using ww_calculate_distance function: function uses geosphere::distm function calculate distance meters fixed point. can see new columns added data.

title: Analysis of SensorLog Data
text: Now distance point time, can summarize data. many cases, need data sub-second second-level. can summarize data daily level using ww_summarize_sensorlog function. function take mean period seconds, usually 60:
code: df_min = ww_minute_sensorlog(df) head(df_min) #> # A tibble: 6 × 16 #>   time                max_speed   lat   lon speed accel_X accel_Y accel_Z #>   <dttm>                  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl>   <dbl> #> 1 2025-03-11 18:44:00        -1  39.3 -76.6    -1 -0.0178   0.964  0.0182 #> 2 2025-03-11 18:45:00        -1  39.3 -76.6    -1 -0.0665   1.01   0.0577 #> 3 2025-03-11 18:46:00        -1  39.3 -76.6    -1 -0.0547   1.00   0.0250 #> 4 2025-03-11 18:47:00        -1  39.3 -76.6    -1 -0.0843   1.01   0.0450 #> 5 2025-03-11 18:48:00        -1  39.3 -76.6    -1 -0.0808   1.01   0.0468 #> 6 2025-03-11 18:49:00        -1  39.3 -76.6    -1 -0.0901   1.01   0.0411 #> # ℹ 8 more variables: distance <dbl>, is_within_home <lgl>, #> #   distance_traveled <dbl>, vm <dbl>, enmo <dbl>, lat_zero <lgl>, #> #   lon_zero <lgl>, in_sensorlog <lgl> df_sum = ww_summarize_sensorlog(df) df_sum #> # A tibble: 1 × 11 #>   date       n_minutes_with_distance sum_distance max_distance #>   <date>                       <int>        <dbl>        <dbl> #> 1 2025-03-11                      12         880.         73.3 #> # ℹ 7 more variables: n_minutes_with_distance_traveled <int>, #> #   sum_distance_traveled <dbl>, mean_distance_traveled <dbl>, #> #   n_distance_traveled <int>, time_within_home <int>, time_outside_home <int>, #> #   time_missing_home <int>

title: Analysis of SensorLog Data
text: also summarize activity profile different levels proximity fixed point read GT3X data. data captured using ActiGraph (Pensacola FL) GT9X device. data stored extdata folder package, similar SensorLog data. get path via ww_example_gt3x_file. can read data using read.gt3x package, waterways wraps using ww_read_gt3x: ActiLife, ActiGraph software, values zero axes set last observation carried forward (LOCF). fill_zeroes argument (default) apply . Also, data read using read.gt3x: > DateTimes therefore represented POSIXct format ‘GMT’ timezone attribute, false; datetime actually represents local time. apply_tz argument ww_read_gt3x (default) find timezone header file, apply data. done using lubridate::with_tz function. timezone stored header file, can seen using attr(ag, "header"). timezone stored TimeZone field. data GMT, “correct” since local time projected GMT. example, measured data timezone -04:00 read.gt3x gave value 2025-03-25 14:14:00, true time GMT 2025-03-25 18:14:00. Using read.gt3x, time incorrectly 2025-03-25 14:14:00 GMT, ww_read_gt3x 2025-03-25 18:14:00 GMT. means want convert timezones, need use lubridate::with_tz lubridate::force_tz. can check timezone data using lubridate::tz function: can confirm via header: can calculate number summary measures acceleration. calculate ActiGraph Activity Counts using agcounts package. use epoch = 60 calculate counts 60-second epochs. counts, can estimate non-wear using Choi (Choi et al. 2011) algorithm, use actigraph.sleepr package. ww_process_gt3x perform operations together:
code: file_gt3x = ww_example_gt3x_file() file_gt3x #> [1] "/home/runner/work/_temp/Library/waterways/extdata/TAS1H30182789_2025-03-11.gt3x.gz" ag = ww_read_gt3x(file_gt3x, verbose = FALSE) head(ag) #>                  time      X     Y     Z #> 1 2025-03-11 17:45:00 -0.270 0.910 0.352 #> 2 2025-03-11 17:45:00 -0.266 0.895 0.359 #> 3 2025-03-11 17:45:00 -0.270 0.887 0.375 #> 4 2025-03-11 17:45:00 -0.281 0.875 0.391 #> 5 2025-03-11 17:45:00 -0.289 0.863 0.406 #> 6 2025-03-11 17:45:00 -0.285 0.859 0.418 lubridate::tz(ag$time) #> [1] "GMT" header = attributes(ag)$header header #> GT3X information #>  $ Serial Number     :"TAS1H30182789" #>  $ Device Type       :"Link" #>  $ Firmware          :"1.7.2" #>  $ Battery Voltage   :"4.17" #>  $ Sample Rate       :80 #>  $ Start Date        : POSIXct, format: "2025-03-11 13:45:00" #>  $ Stop Date         : POSIXct, format: "1-01-01" #>  $ Last Sample Time  : POSIXct, format: "2025-03-11 15:43:15" #>  $ TimeZone          :"-04:00:00" #>  $ Download Date     : POSIXct, format: "2025-03-11 15:43:15" #>  $ Board Revision    :"8" #>  $ Unexpected Resets :"0" #>  $ Acceleration Scale:256 #>  $ Acceleration Min  :"-8.0" #>  $ Acceleration Max  :"8.0" #>  $ Sex               :"Male" #>  $ Race              :"White / Caucasian" #>  $ Limb              :"Wrist" #>  $ Side              :"Left" #>  $ Dominance         :"Non-Dominant" #>  $ Subject Name      :"John" #>  $ Serial Prefix     :"TAS" header$TimeZone #> [1] "-04:00:00" counts = ww_process_gt3x(ag, verbose = FALSE) #> Joining with `by = join_by(timestamp)` counts %>%    head() #> # A tibble: 6 × 6 #>   time                axis1 axis2 axis3 counts wear  #>   <dttm>              <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>  <dbl> <lgl> #> 1 2025-03-11 13:45:00     0     0     0      0 FALSE #> 2 2025-03-11 13:46:00     0     0     0      0 FALSE #> 3 2025-03-11 13:47:00     0     0     0      0 FALSE #> 4 2025-03-11 13:48:00     0     0     0      0 FALSE #> 5 2025-03-11 13:49:00     0     0     0      0 FALSE #> 6 2025-03-11 13:50:00     0     0     0      0 FALSE counts = counts %>% select(time, counts, wear)
